<F P=100> LIFE SCIENCES </F>
<F P=101> EPIDEMIOLOGY, MICROBIOLOGY, AND VIROLOGY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Principles of Biological Safety in Handling Pathogenic 
Microorganisms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  947C0100B Moscow GIGIYENA I SANITARIYA in Russian No. 5-6, 
92 (manuscript received 03 Dec 90) pp 57-59 </F>

<F P=103> 947C0100B </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow GIGIYENA I SANITARIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by L.S. Dzhindoyan and A.Ye. Naydeenov, Scientific </F>
Research Institute of Microbiology, Ministry of Defense, Kirov; 
UDC 613.636:616-078] 
  [Abstract] A common approach to safety 
in the handling of pathogenic microorganisms in microbiological 
laboratories is based on the probability of biological effects 
resulting from exposure to a microorganism or its metabolites. 
This approach also entails definition of socially acceptable 
risk vis-a-vis a defined endpoint, e.g., death. The suggestion 
is made that safety be calculated in terms of probability that 
protective barriers might be overcome by the pathogen per hour 
of work and be released into the working area. For microbiology 
laboratories concerned with pathogens the recommendation is made 
that the acceptable probability for such an event be set at 
10[.sup]-8[/] h[.sup]-1[/]. Figures 3; references 22: 10 
Russian, 12 Western. 

</TEXT>

